The chief magis- trates were two suffetes, or kings, who seem to have been elected annually out os some few principal families: these also furnished a senate of three hundred members, and these again a smaller council of thirty principes. Livy, after the second Punic war, speaks osan assembly of one hundred judges, who held office sor life, and were powerful enough to overrule all the other assemblies and magis- tracies of the state. Hannibal passed a law which checked the power of these judges, causing them to be elected for only one year.
